<TEXT>
facts and figures about lesotho 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the land lesotho entirely inside the borders of south africa 
is a mountainous kingdom covering 11720 square miles roughly the 
size of maryland 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people virtually all of lesothos approximately 16 
million people are from the indigenous basotho tribe roughly 70 
percent of the people are christian about 45 percent of them roman 
catholics english and sesotho are the official languages maseru 
with about 100000 people is the capital and largest city roughly 
onehalf of the adult male labor force works as migrant laborers in 
south african mines about 55 percent of the people are literate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the economy at present the countrys most lucrative natural 
resource is water it has signed an agreement with south africa to 
sell water from the massive multimilliondollar lesotho highlands 
water project construction of which has just begun only 13 
percent of the land is able to be cultivated and 20 percent of the 
countrys food must be imported some smallscale mining and 
manufacturing exist 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history formerly known as basutoland lesotho was the scene of 
fighting between the basotho and white afrikaner settlers until 
britain took responsibility for the country and made it a 
protectorate in 1984 it became independent on oct 4 1966 in 
january 1986 military officers overthew the longruling leftist 
prime minister leabua jonathan whose relations with south africa 
had become increasingly strained the military council remains in 
control and administers the government in consultation with king 
moshoeshoe ii 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us experts are conducting further analysis 
to assure themselves that the united states did not exceed a 
nuclear testing limit during a joint experiment with the soviets 
last month 
the explosive yield from the aug 17 test was supposed to have 
been about 140 kilotons equivalent to 140000 tons of tnt 
however instruments indicated it may have been as high as 153 
kilotons to 160 kilotons 
the corrtex devices used to measure the force of the blast are 
thought to have a margin of error of 30 percent and assistant 
defense secretary ron lehman said wednesday that preliminary 
analysis indicates the blast actually was below the 150 kiloton 
limit set by the 1974 nuclear threshold test ban treaty 
we are doing some chemical analysis lehman said but all 
the signs that we have are that it was under 150 
lehman spoke as us and soviet scientists were conducting the 
second half of the joint verification experiment which americans 
hope will sell the russians on corrtex a system of measuring the 
size of a nuclear blast by means of a cable sunk adjacent to the 
test site 
the soviets for the first time allowed us government 
scientists to monitor an explosion wednesday at a soviet test site 
and permitted american reporters to cover the event from the scene 
the official news agency tass said the explosion had a force 
of 100 kilotons to 150 kilotons 
if the soviets agree to the use of corrtex in addition to 
seismic devices for measuring superpower nuclear tests the two 
sides are expected to sign protocols to the threshold test ban 
treaty and the related 1976 peaceful nuclear explosions treaty 
limiting the size of nuclear blasts for engineering purposes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

