<TEXT>
president reagans saturday radio talks which 
started six years ago as a vehicle for him to speak directly to the 
people about his programs are sounding more and more like weekly 
campaign speeches for george bush 
there has been no suggestion that the broadcasts be treated as 
paid political advertisements as they were when reagan ran for 
reelection in 1984 but democrats and republicans agree there has 
been a sharp increase in political content 
it is appropriate to make political remarks in the context of 
government and administration programs says white house 
spokesman marlin fitzwater also there is a democratic response 
and a democratic opportunity to make the same kind of remarks 
which they take advantage of 
the president has stepped up the heat on the debate said 
another administration source speaking on condition of anonymity 
he has engaged himself more fully in the political dialogue that 
is going on 
its just not unexpected said a democratic source on 
capitol hill where democrats coordinate their weekly broadcast 
response to the presidents speech 
fitzwater said the big difference between now and 1984 when 
reagans speeches became political ads paid for by the republican 
national committee is that the president is not a candidate for 
reelection this year 
the man who is running for his job vice president george bush 
is getting plenty of help from him however 
his name does tend to pop up in the speeches the 
administration source said 
it popped up seven times for instance on aug 13 when the 
president devoted his speech to a preview of the republican 
national convention 
it popped up twice on july 30 when the president talked about 
his central american policies and mentioned that he and bush had 
both visited ailing salvadoran president jose napoleon duarte in 
his hospital room 
it popped up again last saturday when reagan reviewed 
administration educational policy and said george bush and i 
have been there with a sympathetic ear and a helping hand 
and then there was the labor day weekend address on sept 3 
when the president talked about the administrationbacked job 
partnership training act and threw in the fact that it was 
sponsored chiefly by sen dan quayle the gop candidate for vice 
president 
even when he isnt mentioning anybody by name reagans radio 
words are vintage campaign rhetoric 
on aug 6 he said it was just eight years ago that americas 
defenses were in a pitiable state 
on aug 13 he said some in the other party are talking 
about what they claim theyd do if they were elected well while 
they talk we deliver 
on aug 27 he said before we took office in 1981 the globe 
was reeling from an explosion of international turbulence 
on sept 3 he said that in the year we took office the 
average family made only about 70 percent of what it needed to buy 
a new home today that family makes 110 percent of what it needs 
and it can afford to buy the house 
administration officials maintain that the presidents radio 
speeches are for the most part philosophical rather than 
partisan drawing the line between liberals and conservatives 
rather than lambasting the opposition 
that other party that was in party eight years ago however 
is called the democrats 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
w dale nelson covers the white house for the 
associated press 
</TEXT>
