<DOCNO> AP880915-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department has moved closer to 
implementing new rules to help thousands of farmers rearrange their 
debts and hang on to their land 
a new interim rule that is a major step in putting into 
effect some of the key provisions of the agricultural credit act of 
1987 was officially published wednesday a step in the federal 
rulemaking procedure 
many of the laws provisions have already been put into effect 
but some including massive writedowns of farmers debts to the 
farmers home administration will take effect this fall 
proposed rules were initially announced may 23 and specified a 
30day period for public comment the next step was adoption of the 
interim rule 
by doing this the farmers home administration served notice 
that it intends to put the new rules into effect in 30 days or on 
oct 14 in addition the agency specified a 60day comment period 
meaning the public can have its say until midnovember before fmha 
makes its decisions final 
meanwhile according to fmha officials the interim rule clears 
the way for agency field offices to begin carrying out some of the 
most important parts of the 1987 credit act including 
restructuring or writedown of debt 
this provision will allow fmha to reduce a farmers delinquent 
debt to the recovery value of the collateral which is usually land 
or farm equipment depending on cash flow and other factors 
a preliminary regulator impact analysis was published by the 
agency last may and a summary of the report was updated and 
included in the interim rule published this week 
the analysis showed that of about 118000 borrowers delinquent 
in early 1986 about 37000 were considered able to resolve 
delinquency through normal servicing actions including 
subordination rescheduling and deferral of debt 
of the remaining 81000 borrowers eligible for consideration of 
restructuring with writedown of debt about 16000 were estimated 
to be able to show they could repay their remaining debt thereby 
qualifying for the writedown 
an estimated 54000 were estimated to be unable to show 
repayment ability and would be rejected for writedown 
the remaining 11000 were said to be ineligible for writedowns 
because their debt was less than recovery value from liquidation of 
their assets 
according to the analysis the loss to fmha could total 27 
billion for writedown of debt owed by the borrowers able to cash 
flow and 67 billion for those unable to qualify however those 
losses could be reduced by an estimated 1 billion through 
provisions allowing fmha to recapture some of the debt 
the agencys document summarized some of the 247 comments 
received after the initial proposal was made last may some of the 
general comments received by fmha included 
i am happy to see that small farmers can have their debts 
written down to where they can handle it and stay in business 
the regulations are unfair to those who have to pay their debts 
in full at higher interest rates 
the regulations are discriminatory 
keeping these farmers in business adds to the surplus on one 
hand while on the other hand the government buys up the surplus 
and supports prices 
credit is too easy the government should foreclose 
many fmha borrowers are poor managers they spend money they do 
not have 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department says it erred in 
giving out a telephone number for people to call offering comments 
on a proposal to allow a mixture of salvaged meat and bone in 
hotdogs without stating the ingredients on labels 
a terse correction notice by the departments information 
office said wednesday that all comments should be submitted in 
writing by nov 8 
dave warren usda press chief said agency officials were not 
prepared to take oral comments so theyll have to be in writing 
the proposal was announced by usda on monday it would allow 
processors to include a mixture of salvaged meat including small 
bits of bone to be used in up to 10 percent of the meat content of 
hotdogs and similar items without showing the ingredients on 
product labels 
the salvaged product designated as mss or mechanically 
separated species such as pork or beef is made by grinding up 
ribs neckbones and other hardtocarve parts of slaughtered 
animals and forcing the mixture through sieves 
most of the bone particles are screened out but some about 
the size of ground pepper flakes remain in the mixture 
current regulations permit the mss to comprise up to 20 
percent of the meat portion of hotdogs bologna and other sausages 
but the labels must state the contents 
processors who asked for the exemption from the labeling rule 
said they cant sell consumers on the idea of having such a mixture 
in hotdogs under the present labeling requirement 
the written comments can be sent by nov 8 to policy office 
attn linda carey hearing clerk food safety and inspection 
service us department of agriculture room 3171s washington 
dc 20250 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
world sugar production in 198889 is expected 
to be a record of about 1071 million metric tons up 3 percent 
from slightly less than 1038 million tons produced in 198788 
says the agriculture department 
the new estimate also was up from the 1039 million tons 
forecast in june the department said wednesday in a report 
substantial improvements are foreseen for some of the worlds 
major sugar caneproducing countries including australia brazil 
cuba and india the report said unusually good conditions have 
also boosted production estimates for the sugar beet crops now 
being harvested in the european economic community and the soviet 
union 
production of us beet and cane sugar in 198889 was forecast 
at 68 million tons raw value down 67 percent from last seasons 
record 729 million tons 
</TEXT>
