<TEXT>
the solution to africas vast and complex food 
problems will require the heavy use of farming technologies adapted 
to local methods says the office of technology assessment a 
nonpartisan research agency of congress 
existing ways of farming which can vary greatly across the 
continent should be made more productive the ota said wednesday 
it is this lowresource agriculture that offers the best hope 
of producing enough food to keep pace with a growing population 
the agency said in its report to congress that building on 
existing lowresource systems used in african farming herding and 
fishing would work better than trying to replace those methods 
african agriculture faces a major challenge in the next few 
decades the report said it will need to double production to 
keep pace with a growing population and provide an adequate source 
of household income to purchase additional food 
the report said it is uncertain whether technology exists to fit 
africas food problems and whether it can transform lowresource 
agriculture but the report said it is clear some technologies 
and practices do exist and could be used to improve african 
agriculture 
the study was requested by a number of senate and house 
committees involved in hunger science and agriculture the report 
concentrated on that part of africa south of the sahara desert a 
region where food and population problems are most acute 
rep mickey leland dtexas chairman of the house select 
committee on hunger said the ota report was a clear and sharp 
picture of the importance of lowresource agriculture in 
subsaharan africa and the vital necessity of directly assisting 
the poor african farmer in increasing crop production to combat 
chronic hunger 
sen claiborne pell dri said the study shows that the 
lesson of the 1980s is that we can no longer afford the tradeoff 
between shortterm agricultural production increases and longterm 
ecological degradation new methods of agricultural development 
are needed if africa is to achieve a modicum of selfsufficiency 
in its food systems he said 
the ota report said african agriculture for the most part has 
effectively adapted to meet changing conditions but never has the 
pressure been so great 
paramount is the pressure created by rapidly growing 
populations and the consequent demands on the land the report 
said the african continent has the most rapidly growing 
population in the world 29 percent per year in 1988 even if 
this rate slows slightly as expected the continent will have 
triple its current population to feed within just 40 years 
with intensified land use erosion deforestation and other 
abuses yields have declined the report said per capita food 
production and income along with nutritional levels are dropping 
in most areas 
from the late 1960s to the late 1970s africa changed from a 
net exporter of staple foods to a net importer the report said 
in 1986 the value of exports in 22 countries was not sufficient 
to pay for imports 
