<TEXT>
scientists reported today they have compressed 
nuclear fuel to record densities by bombarding it with two dozen 
laser beams a step in developing a new kind of nuclear power 
technology 
but still higher densities will be needed to trigger a nuclear 
reaction called fusion the process that powers the sun 
researchers wrote in the british journal nature 
fusion releases energy as the nucleus or core of one hydrogen 
atom fuses with another todays nuclear plants use another 
reaction fission in which uranium atoms are split to release the 
energy that holds them together 
the new experiments focused on an approach to fusion called 
inertial confinement 
researchers used glass pellets only two to three times the width 
of a human hair the pellets contained the nuclear fuel a frozen 
mix of two forms of hydrogen called deuterium and tritium 
each pellet was bombarded by 24 laser beams the energy heated 
the skin of the pellets causing part of it to blow off that 
provided a rocketlike thrust toward the center of the pellet from 
all sides squeezing the fuel to the high densities 
the fuel reached average densities of 100 to 200 times that of 
its liquid state said robert mccrory of the university of 
rochester who reported the results with rochester colleagues 
to achieve fusion researchers will have to produce densities 
approaching 1000 times that of the liquid state the scientists 
wrote in a telephone interview mccrory said an average of 500 
times typically would be enough because portions of the pellet 
probably would reach the higher mark 
robert kauffman a physicist at the lawrence livermore national 
laboratory in livermore calif called the report another step 
on the way to scientifically demonstrating the feasibility and 
potential of inertial confinement fusion 
</TEXT>
