the house has unanimously approved a bill that 
would increase fines against convicted wall street insider traders 
lengthen their prison terms and penalize investment firms that 
permit the practice 
the measure was passed wednesday by 4100 but its fate is 
unclear in the senate where the legislation may not advance unless 
the house approves a senatepassed banking bill 
when the house measure was debated on tuesday supporters cited 
the steady stream of bigmoney insider trading cases that have 
attracted widespread public attention in recent years 
just last wednesday the investment firm drexel burnham lambert 
inc was named in a civil complaint filed by the securities and 
exchange commission charging insider trading fraud and other 
violations 
the single drumbeats that began two years ago have threatened 
to become a deafening symphony of illegality that would drown out 
the voices of those honest small investors and market professionals 
who seek to be heard in our securities markets said rep edward 
markey dmass chairman of the house telecommunications and 
finance subcommittee where the bill originated 
the legislation would expose securities companies to fines if 
the firm knew or recklessly disregarded that its employees 
committed insider trading violations the fines would be up to 
triple the profits gained or loss avoided or 1 million whichever 
was greater 
maximum criminal fines for insider trading convictions would be 
boosted from 100000 to 1 million for individuals and from 
500000 to 25 million for companies the maximum jail term would 
be doubled to 10 years 
the sec would be allowed to award bounty payments to people 
whose tips result in insider trading prosecutions the bounties 
could be as much as 10 percent of penalty imposed or the settlement 
reached with the convicted trader 
in addition investors who lost money because of insider trading 
would be allowed to seek damages from the insider traders 
sen william proxmire dwis chairman of the senate banking 
committee said last week he is considering withholding similar 
legislation unless house leaders reverse course and agree to move a 
measure giving banks new power to underwrite securities 
