<TEXT>
the reagan administrations top health 
official said today there are some good pros and some good cons 
to using aborted fetal tissue in the experimental treatment of 
various diseases 
health and human services secretary otis r bowen told reporters 
he has not taken a position on the controversial issue of whether 
to recommend federal backing for such research and does not expect 
to until a national institutes of health advisory committee has 
completed a full review of the matter 
bowens comments were his first since the disclosure last week 
that gary bauer a white house domestic policy adviser had drafted 
an executive order that would ban using tissue from intentionally 
aborted fetuses in research 
bauer told bowen in an accompanying memo that he would like the 
secretarys response by last friday because white house officials 
wanted to put the ban into effect as soon as possible 
bowen said today that we have not responded and added that 
he did not intend to make any recommendations until the nih panel 
has completed its work 
asked if he considered the bauer memo an order from the white 
house bowen said i do not know whether it was a direct order 
from the president and i dont know that i will know unless someone 
tells me 
one day after the bauer memo was disclosed white house 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said the draft executive order was just 
a starting point for discussions and did not represent an official 
white house position 
bowen emphasized that he does not approve of abortion but 
added inasmuch as abortions are legal being unable to utilize 
the tissue would result in the waste of a resource that is 
lifesaving and curing for several diseases 
at the same time he said there are some big dangers in the 
widespread use of such treatment including the possibility for a 
sale of fetal tissue by those who intentionally become pregnant and 
then have an abortion with the intent to sell the tissue that 
would be totally wrong 
bowens remarks came during an informal breakfast meeting with 
reporters as the nih panel he referred to was beginning its second 
day of hearings focusing on some of the same ethical issues raised 
by bowen 
a ban against federal financing of such research is likely to 
remain in effect for several months at least 
the nih panel of outside experts consisting of medical legal 
and religious leaders is scheduled to make recommendations friday 
which will be passed on to a standing nih advisory committee and 
ultimately nih director james b wyngaarden 
the threeday meeting of the special advisory panel that started 
wednesday was an outgrowth of a decision by the no 2 official at 
the department of health and human services assistant secretary 
for health robert e windom to deny permission for nih scientists 
to transplant fetal tissue into parkinsons patients pending a full 
airing of legal and ethical questions 
leatrice ducat founder of the juvenile diabetes foundation and 
now operator of a nonprofit organ exchange operation headquartered 
in philadelphia told the group she favored much wider research 
using fetal tissue for diabetes and other diseases 
however she said her organization does not collect and 
distribute fetal tissue to researchers now because the emotional 
climate which makes hospitals and other institutions where 
abortions are performed reluctant to donate fetal tissue 
william f colliton a retired gynecologist and obstetrician 
representing right to life of maryland appeared before the panel 
to oppose the research 
this proposition further devalues our preborn brothers and 
sisters and lends an aura of respectability to the elective killing 
of these patients who today have no protection under the law he 
said 
dr myron genel a pediatrics professor and associate dean for 
government and community affairs at the yale university school of 
medicine told the committee the association of american medical 
colleges and the association of american universities favor fetal 
tissue transplant research with proper safeguards 
while the decision to halt federal involvement in this 
research was guided by ethical concerns equally compelling ethical 
concerns are raised by proposals to enjoin this research 
permanently and thereby to preclude the alleviation of suffering 
and illness in the living genel said 
although not spelled out his reference to proposals for a 
permanent ban apparently referred to a proposed white house 
executive order distributed to federal officials the document 
disclosed by news reports last week had not been intended for 
public consumption 
genels suggestion that ethical questions also would be raised 
by a permanent ban echoed the sentiments expressed earlier 
wednesday by a swedish physician who is one of the few people in 
the world to have transplanted fetal tissue into the brains of 
parkinsons patients 
dr lars olson professor of neurobiology at karolinska 
institute in stockholm told the panel the technique also has been 
used in mexico china england and cuba 
there are no known cases of fetal tissue being transplanted as a 
treatment for parkinsons disease in the united18 
