<TEXT>
the us industrial operating rate rose for 
the fifth consecutive month in august but economists played down 
the inflationary effect of the increase because it was entirely 
attributable to a temporary summer surge at utilities 
the federal reserve board said thursday that the nations 
factories mines and utilities operated at 837 percent of capacity 
last month a 01 percentage point increase over july when the 
rate had risen a sharp 06 percent 
it was the fifth consecutive increase and the highest rate in 
more than eight years industry last operated at 837 percent of 
capacity in march 1980 
economists believe an overall operating rate approaching 85 
percent signals higher prices as industry strains to meet demand 
the operating rate at utilities jumped by 17 percentage points 
in august to 824 percent the rate at plants churning out 
electricity to meet the demand of air conditioners during the 
summer heat wave soared 19 percentage points to 869 percent the 
highest since 1979 
however analysts expect the strain on utilities to ease as the 
weather cools and they pointed to a slight decline in the operating 
rate in the closelywatched manufacturing sector the first since 
february as the more significant number in thursdays report 
overall the manufacturing rate eased from 839 percent in july 
to 838 percent in august 
the rate at factories making durable goods big ticket items 
expected to last three or more years held steady at 823 percent 
in august while the rate at factories producing nondurable goods 
fell from 861 percent in july to 859 percent 
i think industrial capacity has peaked thats the highest 
its going to get for awhile said michael k evans a private 
economist in washington thats good news for inflation 
fighters 
evans said the export boom of the past year which has pushed 
manufacturing operating rates up by 23 percentage points since 
august 1987 is starting to wane 
exports are still growing but at a more normal pace he 
said 
durable goods manufacturing held steady despite a 05 percentage 
point jump in operating rates at steel and other metal 
manufacturing plants the august level 91 percent was 8 
percentage points higher than a year ago 
however rates at auto plants fell to 704 percent last month 
down from 714 percent in july and a peak this year of 753 percent 
in june 
the rate for the mining sector which includes oil and gas 
drilling fell from 830 percent in july to 829 percent 
</TEXT>
