<TEXT>
employees are more likely to sue now 
when theyve been fired than they were at the start of the decade 
according to a study released thursday 
the average employees initial demand was slightly less than the 
average payment after trial and businesses considering legal 
expenses only would be better off paying initial demands rather 
than going to trial the study said 
the study was conducted by james n dertouzos elaine holland 
and patricia ebener of the rand corps institute for civil 
justice rand is a nonprofit private thinktank that analyzes 
national security and public welfare issues 
the researchers reviewed nationwide case law and trial patterns 
through january 1987 sampled los angeles superior court filings 
since 1980 and analyzed california trials from 1980 to 1986 
trials were 2 times more likely in california indiana 
massachusetts montana and north dakota which rand described as 
the five states with the most liberal interpretations of the law 
the study found that in los angeles superior court alone 
wrongful termination lawsuits grew from 90 in 1980 to 600 in 1986 
the researchers found in the california cases that initial jury 
awards averaged 650000 but that figure was inflated by a few 
multimilliondollar judgments the median award was 177000 
however posttrial reductions in jury awards to successful 
plaintiffs averaged 45 percent 
the typical california plaintiff was 45 years old eight years 
of seniority and yearly earnings of 36000 more than 89 percent 
of plaintiffs were white and nearly 69 percent were men middle 
managers accounted for 398 percent of filings compared to 136 
percent by executives 
in 806 percent of firings the employers claimed inadequate 
performance external economic factors were cited in the other 
discharges 
jury awards rose with the plaintiffs age peaking at age 50 
womens awards appeared to be considerably lower than mens 
the study found 
dertouzos concluded unless you have a very good case dont 
bother very few people are getting big payments if you deserve to 
be fired the likelihood of getting big money is very small 
attorneys collected 40 percent of plaintiffs winnings the 
study found and in california that meant the average lawyers 
share was 81000 lawyers for both sides collectively pocketed 60 
percent of the money changing hands in wrongful discharge cases 
the study said 
</TEXT>
