<TEXT>
an appeals court has ordered the federal aviation 
administration to review its decision requiring commercial airline 
pilots to retire at age 60 officials said thursday 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals vacated the faas decision 
denying 28 pilots an exemption from the retirement rule even 
though they had passed health tests to establish their fitness to 
fly 
the court ordered the faa to reconsider its decision to deny the 
pilots request for an exemption 
the 28 pilots from several major airlines including united and 
eastern had appealed the faas ruling last year directly to the 
appellate court contending older pilots could be given medical and 
psychological tests to determine if theyre fit to fly big jets 
they also argued that their years of experience in the cockpit 
would enhance safety and compensate for undetected physical 
problems the pilots presented evidence that older pilots have 
fewer accidents than younger less experienced pilots said alan m 
serwer a chicago attorney who represented the pilots 
the age 60 rule may be worsening the effect of a current 
shortage of commercial airline pilots serwer said thurday the 
airlines have lowered their standards for employment and theyre 
promoting young pilots very rapidly into slots being vacated in 
fairly large numbers by captains who reach the age 60 cutoff 
certain crashes of the past few years might have been avoided 
had the planes young pilots had more experience with difficult 
flying conditions or with the specific aircraft they were flying 
serwer contended 
he declined to provide specific examples but said the faa 
itself has expressed concern about the lack of experience in the 
cockpit 
the appeals court ruling was issued monday and disclosed 
thursday by serwer 
we have not seen the decision yet and until we do were not 
going to have any reaction or comment said fred farrar a 
spokesman at faa headquarters in washington farrar also declined 
to respond to any of serwers remarks 
united airlines based in the chicago area also declined to 
comment because it hadnt reviewed the ruling said spokeswoman 
sara dornacker 
the faa instituted the age 60 retirement rule in 1960 for all 
pilots flying commercial airliners that carry more than 30 
passengers serwer said it doesnt apply to pilots flying commuter 
airline jets or planes with fewer than 30 passengers or to flight 
engineers the third person in the cockpit on large airline flights 
in their appeal the pilots didnt challenge the retirement rule 
directly aiming instead at the faas decision to deny them an 
exemption to the rule based on their ability to pass flight tests 
and medical screening for heart disease stroke and other potential 
health hazards 
in the appellate court decision judge richard d cudahy wrote 
that the faas consideration of the petition for exemption was 
incomplete the agency he wrote failed to set forth a 
sufficient factual or legal basis for its rejection of the 
petitioners claim that the older pilots edge in experience 
offsets any undetected physical losses 
serwer also contended the faas strict enforcement of the age 60 
rule was arbitrary because the agency grants thousands of 
exemptions to other restrictions even granting exemptions to 
some pilots diagnosed as chronic alcoholics 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

