<TEXT>
the us judicial conference on thursday 
announced plans for some federal courts to videotape their 
proceedings in an experiment that if successful could eliminate 
court stenographers 
the experiment is noteworthy because federal courts unlike many 
of their state counterparts ban all electronic coverage of 
courtroom proceedings 
the judicial conference a 28judge board which sets policy for 
the nations federal courts approved the twoyear videotaping 
experiment in a closed meeting wednesday spokesman david sellers 
said 
the experiment to be conducted in six trial courts and two 
appeals courts is patterned after a program already in place in 
kentucky state courts 
the conference wants to find out whether whether videotapes 
should replace written documents as official records of trial and 
appellate court proceedings 
during the experiment videotaping will supplement a 
stenographic record 
public access to the videotapes is something that has not been 
determined yet sellers said 
the experiment will be monitored by a committee led by us 
district judge richard m bilby of tucson ariz 
sellers said no final decision had been made on which courts 
will use the videotapes but he said federal trial judges in 
philadelphia have expressed interest participation of a federal 
trial court in arizona was possible because of judge bilbys role 
sellers said 
the judicial conference also reported that it is asking congress 
to create 73 new judgeships to eliminate backlogs and ease 
workloads but sellers said the realities are that nothing will 
happen during an election year 
the last increase in the judicial workforce was in 1984 when 
congress authorized creation of 86 judgeships 
the conference is seeking 14 new appeals court judges and 59 
trial judges but 22 of the trial judgeships would last only five 
years 
the conference in 1986 sought 56 additional trial court judges 
and 13 appeals court judges a proposal that went nowhere in 
congress 
there currently are 158 appeals court judges and 548 trial 
judges 
sellers said the judicial conference also approved spending 
70000 to 90000 on closedcircuit television cameras to monitor 
high risk trials 
he said stationary cameras capable of scanning a courtroom will 
be installed in 10 or 12 major cities the cameras will provide a 
video monitor feed to a marshals office 
the us marshals service proposed the security measure 
</TEXT>
