<TEXT>
recent findings about auto pollution could 
make it easier for many cities to meet federal clean air standards 
the head of the environmental protection agency said thursday 
the findings could double the effectiveness of planned agency 
regulations to control the volatility of gasoline and the recovery 
of gasoline fumes 
only in the past year has the agency begun to study what is 
called running loss the evaporation of gasoline from the tank 
and other fuel system components while the car is moving 
gasoline fumes react in sunlight with nitrogen oxides from all 
fuel combustion to produce ozone which is harmful to the lungs 
ozone is the constituent of urban smog that makes the chest feel 
tight 
proposed regulations discussed for years and frequently 
postponed for reworking had been calculated to reduce urban 
gasoline emissions by 10 percent or 15 percent epa administrator 
lee m thomas said at luncheon for reporters 
a new calculation of running loss suggests the effectiveness of 
the planned regulations could be as much as twice that thomas 
said 
this could mean cities close to compliance with federal clean 
air standards will have an easier time meeting the requirements and 
may not have to launch programs to inspect auto exhausts and 
pollution control systems he said 
i mean the marginal cities where reductions in hydrocarbons of 
zero to 25 percent would be required thomas said 
thomas said he could not say which closetocompliance cities 
might comply under the planned regulations but those most favored 
would be areas with peak concentrations in the 014 parts per 
million range and below 
the federal standard calls for limiting peak ozone to 012 parts 
per million and limiting excursions above that to no more than one 
hour per year 
epas list of noncomplying areas contains 68 urban and rural 
areas 38 of them with peaks of 014 ppm and below 
federal regulations have long governed how much unburned 
gasoline could be emitted in exhaust and how much could be 
evaporated while the car is stationary but epa has ignored 
evaporation while running in the belief that the amounts escaping 
vapor recovery systems were negligible 
gasoline volatility has risen throughout the 1980s and greater 
volatility brings increased emissions through evaporation 
exxon corp scientists revealed in may that their own and epa 
tests showed vapor recovery systems on cars were being overwhelmed 
on hot days releasing to the atmosphere perhaps 25 times as much 
gasoline as was permitted in exhaust 
the proposed regulations will remove most of this important and 
previously unknown source of ozone 
epa scientists said at the time it was an important discovery 
but they had not had a chance to calculate what the new findings 
would mean for urban ozone pollution thomas disclosure thursday 
was the first such assessment 
thomas said he planned to republish the regulations in final 
form for public comment in plenty of time to adopt them before the 
reagan administration leaves office 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880915-0178 </DOCNO>
