about education reforms a national school boards association panel 
said thursday 
while most public school systems participate in collective 
bargaining with their teacher organizations the adversarial nature 
of these discussions has worked against cooperation and candor in 
some instances the panel said in a 44page report 
the panel was convened last year by the associations 
thenpresident jonathan t howe who is a local school board member 
in northbrook ill to look into how we get into these 
situations of strikes at the opening of school terms each 
september 
the report comes on the heels of carnegie foundation survey 
released this week showing that teachers believe they have little 
role in key classroom decisions and want more authority and 
responsibility 
howe said he agreed with the foundations conclusions that 
teachers should have more to say about such things but not through 
collective bargaining by their unions 
collective bargaining today is what i call pmp power 
money and process he said these are the three items that 
normally get discussed at the bargaining table it is nearly 
impossible to discuss working cooperatively for the benefit of 
school children after hours of debate solely on pay scales 
benefits and length of contract 
howe said unionheralded education reform efforts in dade 
county fla and rochester ny came about not through 
collective bargaining but through a waiver of collective bargaining 
to bring about change 
albert shanker president of the american federation of 
