<TEXT>
iraq will not agree to lower its output of oil 
even if other opec members ask and may even increase production 
the countrys oil minister said in an interview published thursday 
the minister issam abdulrahim alchalabi told the alwatan 
newspaper that iraq would not rule out increasing its output from 
27 million barrels a day as part of an effort to rebuild its 
shattered economy after eight years of war with iran 
iraq has refused to abide by a quota of 15 million barrels a 
day set by the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
because its persian gulf enemy has been allowed to produce 23 
million barrels a day 
opec secretarygeneral subroto has held talks with several 
members of the cartel recently including iran who are opposed to 
raising iraqs official quota to parity with iran 
however the newspaper thursday said chalabis latest statements 
indicate baghdad no longer is interested in gaining parity with 
iran or in accepting any assigned quota 
we sacrificed and lost a lot in the eight years of hostilities 
during which we could not produce our output quota the minister 
was quoted as saying 
therefore we are not prepared to sacrifice more as we now 
have our construction commitments and debt which we should repay 
the minister declined to estimate by how much iraq might 
increase its oil exports saying it would depend to a large 
extent on the state of our ports 
but our output will be larger when the second stage of the 
iraqisaudi pipeline is completed in september 1989 he said 
the pipeline to the red sea and another via turkey to the 
mediterranean were oil export outlets iraq used after its ports 
were damaged and shipments through the gulf blocked by the war 
oil prices have risen sharply in recent days after a steady 
decline in previous weeks prompted by fears of a world oversupply 
of oil the sharp rise in prices started monday was fueled by 
reports suggesting that opec could be closer to limiting production 
chalabi dismissed as baseless charges that iraq was 
responsible for the overall decline in oil prices saying iraqi 
production did not change whereas oil prices dropped by 30 
percent 
opec is producing at least 35 million barrels a day more than 
its selfimposed collective quota of 15 million barrels crude is 
selling between 14 and 1550 a barrel on world markets opecs 
benchmark price is 18 
the new yorkbased petroleum intelligence weekly reported in 
august that iraq was exporting 500000 barrels of oil a day to the 
united states 
chalabi said that talk of a us embargo of iraqi oil because of 
iraqs alleged use of chemical weapons against turkish refugees did 
not worry him 
iraq will be able to find markets for selling its oil and 
consequently our oil exports will not be affected by any embargo 
chalabi said 
