the asiapacific region will be the fastest 
growing economic area in the world in the 1990s a study predicted 
thursday 
but unlike past years when exports from japan korea taiwan 
hong kong and singapore to the rest of the world fueled the 
regions progress the engine of growth in the next decade will be 
trade among the areas 12 nations the report said 
the 60page study was prepared by sri international a research 
firm and released by the worldlwide accounting firm kpmg peat 
marwick 
the united states and western europe will not support further 
large increases in asiapacific exports the report said 
therefore the region will have to depend to a greater extent 
than in the past on trade within the region and on development of 
their domestic economies 
it forecast the annual growth rate for the region would average 
about two percentage points higher than the world as a whole over 
the 1990s 
among the reports predictions for the region 
china will have the fastest growing economy averaging 67 
percent a year but its percapita income will still be the lowest 
of the 12 nations 
the newly industrializing countries south korea hong kong 
singapore and taiwan will continue to experience strong growth 
but at a slower pace than during the past several decades south 
korea is expected to have average growth of around 65 percent a 
year with the other three ranging between 55 percent and 6 
percent 
growth in thailand and malaysia will average 5 percent a year 
indonesia and the philippines will continue to have the weakest 
economies with average annual growth rates of 4 percent and 3 
percent respectively 
the three developed countries in the region japan australia 
and new zealand will have the slowest growth rates japan will 
lead the trio with an average annual growth rate of slightly more 
than 3 percent a year 
